#!/usr/bin/env python3
"""oto-sandbox-net — pasta-managed network namespace launcher for agent sandboxes.

Single owner of netns setup for sandboxed local agent sessions (Ordering 1:
pasta spawns the inner command — the netns is fully configured BEFORE the
agent execs, so the permission hook can never hit its fail-open-on-connect
branch during a setup race). Call sites simply prepend this launcher to the
existing bwrap argv; see core/sandbox/sandbox.py::SandboxBuilder.build_command_prefix.

Usage:
    oto-sandbox-net [--forward PORT]... [--allow-host ADDR]... \
                    [--dns-forward ADDR] [--block-private] \
                    -- <inner argv (bwrap ... -- agent ...)>

Behavior:
    1. exec pasta with an EXPLICIT port-forward policy:
       - ``-T <port>`` per --forward: in-netns 127.0.0.1:<port> (and ::1) is
         spliced to init-namespace loopback:<port>. This is the ONLY loopback
         reachability the agent gets (proxy hook port + its T1 Docker MCP ports).
       - ``-t none -u none -U none`` (+ ``-T none`` when no forwards): pasta's
         port-forward defaults are **auto** — it would periodically scan bound
         ports and forward them, silently exposing host services (Postgres
         :5432!). Every direction is therefore pinned explicitly.
       - ``--no-map-gw``: by default pasta maps the gateway address to the
         host's loopback (--map-host-loopback), so an agent could reach host
         services by dialing the gateway IP. Disabled — loopback-addressed
         packets to non-forwarded ports are simply dropped.
       - ``--config-net``: addresses/routes/tap are set up by pasta before the
         child runs. Outbound internet is NAT'd through the host's stack.
    2. A tiny ``python3`` shim runs inside the netns (userns-root has
       CAP_NET_ADMIN over the owned netns) before exec'ing the inner argv:
       - --block-private installs ``unreachable`` routes for the cloud-metadata
         range, the RFC1918 host ranges (10/8, 172.16/12 — covering the Docker
         bridge 172.17.0.1 — 192.168/16, link-local), AND **the host's own
         on-link subnet(s)** (captured at runtime). pasta NATs outbound by
         opening sockets HOST-side, so without these the agent could reach any
         host-routable IP — including same-subnet hosts and metadata; the
         blackholes shadow the default/on-link routes (longest-prefix wins).
         Loopback (127/8) is governed separately by pasta's -T allow-list.
       - Carve-outs (more-specific /32 · /128 via the gateway, so they survive
         the blackholes): the default gateway (egress), the host's non-loopback
         resolvers from /etc/resolv.conf (DNS even with an RFC1918 resolver),
         the --dns-forward ADDR, any non-loopback ``-T`` target, and every
         ``--allow-host ADDR`` (the session's configured MCP / docker-MCP /
         local-LLM targets — see core/sandbox + mcp_registry.resolve_sandbox_egress).
         pasta re-originates the connection host-side, so a via-gateway carve
         reaches an on-link target just as well as a routed one — the nexthop
         only has to get the packet onto the tap.
       - --dns-forward ADDR: pasta intercepts port 53/853 to ADDR and relays to
         the host's real resolver. Used on hosts whose /etc/resolv.conf points
         at a loopback stub (systemd-resolved / Docker embedded DNS) that cannot
         exist inside the netns; core/sandbox/sandbox.py pairs this flag with a generated
         resolv.conf bind-mounted over /etc/resolv.conf.
       Then, before exec'ing the inner argv, the shim repairs ``/proc`` when
       pasta ran it in a NEW pid namespace while leaving ``/proc`` bound to the
       parent pidns (the container ``pasta`` build does this): it gives itself a
       private mount namespace and remounts ``/proc`` so bwrap's userns setup can
       read ``/proc/<pid>/ns/*`` (``_ensure_proc_for_pidns``; a no-op where pasta
       keeps the caller's pidns, e.g. distro pasta on bare metal).
    3. PR_SET_PDEATHSIG(SIGKILL) is set before exec'ing pasta: bwrap's
       --die-with-parent now watches *pasta* (its parent after the wrap), so
       pasta itself must die with the proxy to preserve today's kill chain
       (proxy dies -> pasta killed -> bwrap kills the agent tree). The launcher
       then bails if its parent died in the pre-arm window — detected by the
       parent PID *changing* from the value captured at startup, NOT by a
       ``getppid()==1`` test (the proxy legitimately runs AS pid 1 in a
       container, so an ``==1`` test would abort every spawn).

The launcher runs in the host mount namespace (before bwrap), so it uses the
host's ``pasta``, ``ip`` and ``python3``. Dependency-light by design: stdlib only.

Ordering note: if pasta-spawns-bwrap (O1) ever proves problematic on a host,
the O1->O2 swap (bwrap first, pasta attaches to its netns) is contained
entirely in this file — call sites never change.
"""

import ctypes
import os
import shutil
import signal
import sys

_PR_SET_PDEATHSIG = 1

# Parent (proxy) PID captured the instant the launcher starts — the proxy is
# alive then (it just spawned us). main()'s orphan guard bails only if this
# CHANGES before exec (true reparenting = the proxy died). Hard-coding "== 1"
# is wrong in a container, where the proxy legitimately runs AS pid 1.
_LAUNCH_PPID = os.getppid()

# Ranges blackholed by --block-private. pasta NATs outbound by opening sockets
# on the HOST side, so ANY address the host can route to is reachable from the
# netns unless an `unreachable` route shadows the default route — including the
# host's own non-loopback service IPs (the Docker bridge gateway 172.17.0.1,
# other RFC1918 hosts) and the cloud-metadata range. Loopback (127/8) is NOT
# in this list: it is governed by pasta's `-t none` + explicit `-T` allow-list
# + `--no-map-gw` (the metadata /32s are kept explicit so a future narrowing of
# the /16 can never silently reopen IMDS). This mirrors the WebFetch SSRF
# policy in auth/path_policy. The shim carves the default gateway, the host's
# resolvers, the DNS-forwarder, and any non-loopback `-T` target back OUT of
# these blackholes (more-specific routes win) so egress + DNS + the allow-list
# survive — see _build_shim.
_BLOCK_V4 = (
    "169.254.169.254/32",  # AWS / GCP / Azure / OCI metadata (explicit)
    "169.254.170.2/32",    # AWS ECS task credentials (explicit)
    "10.0.0.0/8",          # RFC1918
    "172.16.0.0/12",       # RFC1918 (covers the Docker default bridge 172.17/16)
    "192.168.0.0/16",      # RFC1918
    "169.254.0.0/16",      # whole link-local range
)
# v6: only the explicit metadata endpoint. Broad v6 ULA (fc00::/7) blocking
# needs a v6 gateway/resolver carve-out that can't be validated on an IPv4-only
# host, and a botched v6 blackhole risks breaking v6 egress — deferred. v6 ULA
# host-service exposure is a lower-likelihood risk than the v4 Docker bridge.
_BLOCK_V6 = (
    "fd00:ec2::254/128",   # AWS IMDSv2 over IPv6 (explicit)
)


def _die(msg: str) -> None:
    print(f"oto-sandbox-net: {msg}", file=sys.stderr)
    sys.exit(127)


def _parse_argv(
    argv: list[str],
) -> tuple[list[str], list[str], str, bool, list[str]]:
    forwards: list[str] = []
    allow_hosts: list[str] = []
    dns_forward = ""
    block_private = False
    i = 0
    while i < len(argv):
        arg = argv[i]
        if arg == "--":
            return forwards, allow_hosts, dns_forward, block_private, argv[i + 1:]
        if arg == "--forward":
            i += 1
            if i >= len(argv):
                _die("--forward requires a port argument")
            forwards.append(argv[i])
        elif arg == "--allow-host":
            i += 1
            if i >= len(argv):
                _die("--allow-host requires an address argument")
            allow_hosts.append(argv[i])
        elif arg == "--dns-forward":
            i += 1
            if i >= len(argv):
                _die("--dns-forward requires an address argument")
            dns_forward = argv[i]
        elif arg in ("--block-private", "--block-metadata"):
            # --block-metadata kept as a back-compat alias for the same flag.
            block_private = True
        else:
            _die(f"unknown argument: {arg!r} (expected --forward/--allow-host/"
                 f"--dns-forward/--block-private/--)")
        i += 1
    _die("missing `--` separator before the inner command")
    raise AssertionError  # unreachable


# The in-netns shim, run by the host python3 as userns-root (CAP_NET_ADMIN over
# the owned netns), AFTER pasta --config-net, BEFORE bwrap. Config is baked in
# via .format(); the inner argv arrives as sys.argv[1:] and is exec'd at the end.
# It:
#   1. reads the default-route gateway/dev pasta installed;
#   2. carves the gateway reachable as an on-link /32 (egress lifeline);
#   3. captures the host's on-link subnet CIDR(s) BEFORE blackholing;
#   4. carves the must-reach set (resolvers + --dns-forward + non-loopback -T
#      targets + every --allow-host) as more-specific /32 · /128 via the gateway
#      — pasta re-originates host-side, so via-gw reaches on-link AND routed;
#   5. blackholes _BLOCK_V4 + the on-link subnet(s) (fail-CLOSED, os._exit(41))
#      and _BLOCK_V6 (tolerated — v6 may be off);
#   6. exec's the inner argv.
_PYSHIM = '''\
import ctypes, os, subprocess, sys
_BLOCK_V4 = {block_v4!r}
_BLOCK_V6 = {block_v6!r}
_CARVE = {carve!r}
_BLOCK = {block!r}

def _ip(args, v6=False):
    cmd = ["ip"] + (["-6"] if v6 else ["-4"]) + args
    return subprocess.run(cmd, stdout=subprocess.PIPE, stderr=subprocess.DEVNULL, text=True)

def _default():
    out = _ip(["-o", "route", "show", "default"]).stdout.split()
    gw = dev = ""
    for i, t in enumerate(out):
        if t == "via" and i + 1 < len(out): gw = out[i + 1]
        elif t == "dev" and i + 1 < len(out): dev = out[i + 1]
    return gw, dev

def _gw6():
    out = _ip(["-o", "route", "show", "default"], v6=True).stdout.split()
    for i, t in enumerate(out):
        if t == "via" and i + 1 < len(out): return out[i + 1]
    return ""

def _resolvers():
    res = []
    try:
        with open("/etc/resolv.conf") as f:
            for ln in f:
                p = ln.split()
                if len(p) >= 2 and p[0] == "nameserver" and p[1] and not p[1].startswith("127.") and p[1] != "::1":
                    res.append(p[1])
    except OSError:
        pass
    return res

def _onlink4():
    nets = []
    for ln in _ip(["-o", "route", "show", "scope", "link"]).stdout.splitlines():
        p = ln.split()
        if p and "/" in p[0] and not p[0].startswith("169.254."):
            nets.append(p[0])
    return nets

def _ensure_proc_for_pidns():
    # pasta may run the inner command in a NEW pid namespace while leaving /proc
    # bound to the parent (container) pidns. bwrap forks a helper during its
    # userns setup and opens /proc/<pid>/ns/* — a stale /proc makes that read
    # fail ("bwrap: open /proc/N/ns/... No such file"), so the agent dies the
    # instant it spawns. Detect the mismatch (our PID as /proc sees it != our
    # real PID) and ONLY then give ourselves a private mount namespace and
    # remount /proc so it reflects this pidns. No-op where pasta keeps the
    # caller's pidns (distro pasta on bare metal), so T1 is unaffected.
    try:
        if os.readlink("/proc/self") == str(os.getpid()):
            return
    except OSError:
        return
    libc = ctypes.CDLL(None, use_errno=True)
    CLONE_NEWNS = 0x00020000
    MS_REC = 16384
    MS_PRIVATE = 1 << 18
    if libc.unshare(CLONE_NEWNS) != 0:
        sys.stderr.write("oto-sandbox-net-shim: warning: unshare(mount-ns) failed errno=" + str(ctypes.get_errno()) + "; bwrap may fail\\n")
        return
    # Private propagation so the proc remount can never leak into the container's
    # shared mount namespace; then remount /proc for the current pid namespace.
    libc.mount(None, b"/", None, MS_REC | MS_PRIVATE, None)
    if libc.mount(b"proc", b"/proc", b"proc", 0, None) != 0:
        sys.stderr.write("oto-sandbox-net-shim: warning: remount /proc failed errno=" + str(ctypes.get_errno()) + "; bwrap may fail\\n")

inner = sys.argv[1:]
if not inner:
    sys.stderr.write("oto-sandbox-net-shim: empty inner argv\\n"); os._exit(127)

gw, dev = _default()
gw6 = _gw6()
if gw and dev:
    _ip(["route", "replace", gw + "/32", "dev", dev])
else:
    sys.stderr.write("oto-sandbox-net-shim: warning: no default route — egress/DNS may fail\\n")

onlink = _onlink4() if _BLOCK else []

def _carve(a):
    if not a:
        return
    if ":" in a:
        if gw6:
            _ip(["route", "replace", a + "/128", "via", gw6], v6=True)
    elif gw:
        _ip(["route", "replace", a + "/32", "via", gw])

for a in _resolvers():
    _carve(a)
for a in _CARVE:
    _carve(a)

if _BLOCK:
    for net in list(_BLOCK_V4) + onlink:
        if _ip(["route", "replace", "unreachable", net]).returncode != 0:
            sys.stderr.write("oto-sandbox-net-shim: failed to blackhole " + net + "\\n")
            os._exit(41)
    for net in _BLOCK_V6:
        _ip(["route", "replace", "unreachable", net], v6=True)

_ensure_proc_for_pidns()
os.execvp(inner[0], inner)
'''


def _build_pyshim(
    forwards: list[str], allow_hosts: list[str],
    dns_forward: str, block_private: bool,
) -> str:
    """The in-netns python3 program (config baked in). See _PYSHIM."""
    # Non-loopback forward targets (`addr/port` specs) carve back out; loopback
    # forwards are plain ports handled by pasta's -T splice.
    fwd_addrs = [f.split("/", 1)[0] for f in forwards
                 if "/" in f and not f.split("/", 1)[0].startswith("127.")]
    carve = ([dns_forward] if dns_forward else []) + fwd_addrs + list(allow_hosts)
    return _PYSHIM.format(
        block_v4=_BLOCK_V4, block_v6=_BLOCK_V6,
        carve=carve, block=block_private,
    )


def main() -> None:
    forwards, allow_hosts, dns_forward, block_private, inner = _parse_argv(sys.argv[1:])
    if not inner:
        _die("empty inner command after `--`")

    pasta = shutil.which("pasta")
    if not pasta:
        _die("`pasta` not found on PATH (install the passt package — see "
             "VERSIONS.md). Refusing to run the agent without network "
             "isolation.")
    python3 = sys.executable or shutil.which("python3")
    if not python3:
        _die("python3 not found — required for the in-netns route shim.")

    cmd = [
        pasta,
        "--quiet",        # info-level chatter off; errors still hit stderr
        "--config-net",   # addresses/routes/tap ready BEFORE the child execs
        "--no-map-gw",    # gateway address must NOT alias the host's loopback
        # Pin every forward direction: pasta defaults to `auto` (scans bound
        # ports!) — only the explicit allowlist below may cross the boundary.
        "-t", "none",
        "-u", "none",
        "-U", "none",
    ]
    if forwards:
        for port in forwards:
            cmd.extend(["-T", port])
    else:
        cmd.extend(["-T", "none"])
    if dns_forward:
        cmd.extend(["--dns-forward", dns_forward])

    pyshim = _build_pyshim(forwards, allow_hosts, dns_forward, block_private)
    cmd.extend(["--", python3, "-c", pyshim, *inner])

    # Preserve the kill chain (see module docstring). prctl survives execve
    # for non-setuid binaries; pasta's static build is plain. If the proxy died
    # in the spawn window (before pdeathsig is armed), getppid() changes from the
    # value captured at startup (reparenting to init/subreaper) — bail rather
    # than orphan. We compare against the captured PID, NOT a hard-coded "== 1":
    # in a container the proxy IS pid 1, so getppid()==1 is the healthy case and
    # an "== 1" test would (wrongly) abort every single agent spawn.
    try:
        libc = ctypes.CDLL(None, use_errno=True)
        libc.prctl(_PR_SET_PDEATHSIG, signal.SIGKILL, 0, 0, 0)
    except Exception:
        pass  # non-Linux/odd libc: lose only the orphan guard, not isolation
    if os.getppid() != _LAUNCH_PPID:
        _die("parent exited before launch")

    # Hand pasta a CLEAN signal state before exec. os.execv preserves this
    # process's signal MASK + dispositions; the proxy spawns this launcher from
    # asyncio, which leaves signals blocked — and pasta fails hard ("Couldn't
    # install signal handlers") if it inherits a blocked mask. A fork+exec child
    # gets this reset for free (subprocess restore_signals); execv does not, so
    # do it explicitly. (Manifests inside the containerized proxy; a bare-metal
    # host happens to inherit a clean mask.)
    try:
        signal.pthread_sigmask(signal.SIG_SETMASK, set())  # unblock everything
        for _sig in range(1, signal.NSIG):
            try:
                signal.signal(_sig, signal.SIG_DFL)  # SIG_IGN → SIG_DFL too
            except (OSError, ValueError, RuntimeError):
                pass  # uncatchable (SIGKILL/SIGSTOP) / invalid — skip
    except Exception:
        pass  # never block the launch on a signal-reset hiccup

    os.execv(pasta, cmd)


if __name__ == "__main__":
    main()
